le=3D"row"><td class=3D"confluenceTd">1/4-20</td><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D=
"confluenceTd">.25</td><td class=3D"confluenceTd">63.9</td><td class=3D"con=
fluenceTd">75.2 in-lbs</td><td class=3D"confluenceTd">143 in-lbs</td><td cl=
ass=3D"confluenceTd">&nbsp;</td></tr><tr role=3D"row"><td colspan=3D"1" cla=
ss=3D"confluenceTd">5/16-18</td><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">.3=
13</td><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">112</td><td colspan=3D"1" c=
lass=3D"confluenceTd">132 in-lbs</td><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceT=
d">295 in-lbs</td><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">&nbsp;</td></tr>=
<tr role=3D"row"><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">3/8-16</td><td co=
lspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">.375</td><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"conf=
luenceTd">201</td><td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">236 in-lbs</td><=
td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">528 in-lbs</td><td colspan=3D"1" cl=
ass=3D"confluenceTd">&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>This will pro=
vide an example on how to calculate the optimal bolt torque, using calculat=
ions for the bolt torque specification of the Hermes 3 motor case.</p><p>Wh=
ile the upper table provides more general information, this section will pr=
ovide more specific calculations.</p><h2 id=3D"RocketTeamBoltSpecifications=
-MaxTensileLoad">Max Tensile Load</h2><p>First we must calculate the maximu=
m tensile load of the bolts being used. This is the measurement of the maxi=
mum amount of tension force the bolt can withstand before it fractures.&nbs=
p; In the case of Hermes 3, we are using 5/16-18 by 5/8" Grade 8 Steel Bolt=
s.&nbsp;</p><p>The equation for this is:</p><p><strong><br></strong></p><p>=
<strong>P =3D St x As</strong></p><p><strong>P</strong> =3D maximum tensile=
 load or clamp load (lbs,. N)</p><p><strong>St</strong> =3D tensile strengt=
h (psi, MPA)</p><p><strong>As</strong> =3D tensile stress area (sq. in, sq.=
 mm)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Using the following&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.eng=
ineersedge.com/fastener_thread_stress_area.htm" class=3D"external-link" rel=
=3D"nofollow">spreadsheet</a>, we find that the tensile stress area of our =
Bolts in inches squared is 0.052. The tensile strength of our material (whi=
ch in this case is Grade 8 Steel), is approximately 150000 lbs/in^2.</p><p>=
From this we can calculate our maximum tensile load:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><st=
rong>P</strong> =3D 0.052 x 150000 =3D=3D 7800 lbs&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p=
>This is the maximum load, however we cannot use this value for calculating=
 our torque specification, because a factor of safety is necessary.&nbsp; T=
he standard for this is around 75% of the calculated maximum tensile load.&=
nbsp; When a safety factor is added, the new value is:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><=
strong>F&nbsp;</strong>(optimal clamp load) =3D 0.75 x 7800 =3D=3D 5850 lbs=
</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h2 id=3D"RocketTeamBoltSpecifications-KValue,ortheNutFact=
or">K Value, or the Nut Factor</h2><p>In the equation for calculating torqu=
e, which is<strong> T</strong> =3D <strong>K</strong> x <strong>d</strong> =
x <strong>F,&nbsp;</strong>the value K is the most variable of the values.&=
nbsp; While&nbsp;<strong>d</strong> (the nominal diameter) and <strong>F&nb=
sp;</strong>(the clamp force) have very simple calculations to acquire thei=
r values,&nbsp;<strong>K</strong> is much more complex.&nbsp;</p><p><span s=
tyle=3D"font-size: 10.0pt;">In simple terms,&nbsp;</span><strong style=3D"f=
ont-size: 10.0pt;">K</strong><span style=3D"font-size: 10.0pt;"> can be tho=
ught of as a measurement of anything that increases or decreases friction b=
etween the threads of the nut. A more in depth description of&nbsp;</span><=
strong style=3D"font-size: 10.0pt;">K</strong><span style=3D"font-size: 10.=
0pt;">&nbsp;and its factors can be found in this&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.fastenal.com/content/feds/pdf/Article%20-%20Bolted%20Joint%20Desig=
n.pdf" style=3D"font-size: 10.0pt;" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow=
">guide</a><span style=3D"font-size: 10.0pt;"> on fasteners. In this wiki p=
age, we will just provide more basic estimations of the </span><strong styl=
e=3D"font-size: 10.0pt;">K</strong><span style=3D"font-size: 10.0pt;"> valu=
e needed.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><div class=3D"table-wrap"><table class=3D"=
confluenceTable tablesorter tablesorter-default" role=3D"grid"><thead><tr r=
ole=3D"row" class=3D"tablesorter-headerRow"><th class=3D"confluenceTh table=
sorter-header sortableHeader tablesorter-headerUnSorted" data-column=3D"0" =
tabindex=3D"0" scope=3D"col" role=3D"columnheader" aria-disabled=3D"false" =
unselectable=3D"on" aria-sort=3D"none" aria-label=3D"K Factors: No sort app=
lied, activate to apply an ascending sort" style=3D"user-select: none;"><di=
v class=3D"tablesorter-header-inner">K Factors</div></th><th class=3D"confl=
uenceTh tablesorter-header sortableHeader tablesorter-headerUnSorted" data-=
column=3D"1" tabindex=3D"0" scope=3D"col" role=3D"columnheader" aria-disabl=
ed=3D"false" unselectable=3D"on" aria-sort=3D"none" aria-label=3D"&nbsp;: N=
o sort applied, activate to apply an ascending sort" style=3D"user-select: =
none;"><div class=3D"tablesorter-header-inner">&nbsp;</div></th></tr></thea=
d><tbody aria-live=3D"polite" aria-relevant=3D"all"><tr role=3D"row"><td cl=
ass=3D"confluenceTd"><strong>Bolt Condition </strong></td><td class=3D"conf=
luenceTd"><strong>K</strong></td></tr><tr role=3D"row"><td class=3D"conflue=
nceTd">Non-Plated, black finish (dry)</td><td class=3D"confluenceTd">0.20 -=
 0.30</td></tr><tr role=3D"row"><td class=3D"confluenceTd">Zinc-Plated</td>=
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">0.17- 0.22</td></tr><tr role=3D"row"><td class=
=3D"confluenceTd">Lubricated</td><td class=3D"confluenceTd">0.12 - 0.16</td=
></tr><tr role=3D"row"><td class=3D"confluenceTd">Cadmium-plated</td><td cl=
ass=3D"confluenceTd">0.11-0.15</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>&nbsp;</p>=
<p>The bolts we are using are non-plated black finish, so the <strong>K</st=
rong> value we will use for this calculation of the torque will be 0.20</p>=
<p><u>Side Note</u>: One reason we do not used zinc-plated bolts is because=
 zinc becomes a gas at 300 degrees C, and our rocket burns at around 2800 d=
egrees C.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h2 id=3D"RocketTeamBoltSpecifications-Torq=
ueCalculation">Torque Calculation</h2><p>Now that we have our tensile load =
value, as well as our K factor value, the optimal torque can be calculated.=
&nbsp;</p><p>The equation for torque, as mentioned previously, is:</p><p>&n=
bsp;</p><p><strong>T =3D K x d x F</strong></p><p><strong>K =3D&nbsp;</stro=
ng>Nut Factor</p><p><strong>d =3D&nbsp;</strong>nominal diameter of the bol=
t (in,. mm)</p><p><strong>F</strong> =3D tensile load (lbs., N)</p><p>&nbsp=
;</p><p>For our bolts the diameter is 5/16 of an inch, or 0.3125 inches. So=
 our calculation is:</p><p><strong>T</strong> =3D 0.2 x 0.3125 x 5850 =3D=
=3D 365.625 in/lbs</p><p>365.625/12 =3D=3D 30.5 ft/lbs</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>3=
0.5 ft/lbs is now our final value for the optimal torque. This is necessary=
 to guarantee that the bolt is not too loose (which would cause our seal to=
 not be as strong), or too tight (which would deform our bolts and potentia=
lly damage the material being clamped).&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><hr><h1 id=3D=
"RocketTeamBoltSpecifications-MotorCaseBoltShearStressCalculation">Motor Ca=
se Bolt Shear Stress Calculation</h1><p>When building a motor with a radial=
ly bolted case, you must make sure that your bolts will be able to stand up=
 to the forces applied to them. To demonstrate this, we will look at the Ph=
oenix booster as an example.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Calculated Booster Ma=
x Booster Pressure =3D 826 psi</p><p>Forward Closure Inner Area =3D 10 in^2=
</p><p>Number of Bolts =3D 24</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>First, we must calculate t=
he force on the forward closure due to this pressure.</p><p><strong>F =3D P=
*A</strong></p><p><strong>F =3D&nbsp;</strong>826*10 =3D 8260 lbs</p><p>&nb=
sp;</p><p>This force is assumed to be perfectly distributed among each bolt=
, so the force on each bolt is:</p><p>8260/24 =3D 344.16 lbs</p><p>&nbsp;</=
p><p>Our bolt is under a single shear, which looks like the reference diagr=
am below. In order to evaluate the shear stress, we need to use the equatio=
n on the right. Our bolts have a diameter of 1/4 of an inch.&nbsp;</p><p><s=
pan class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-si=
ze"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image confluence-external-resource" d=
raggable=3D"false" width=3D"300" src=3D"https://forums.autodesk.com/t5/imag=
e/serverpage/image-id/46829iC9C1CE720C0A71D8?v=3D1.0" data-image-src=3D"htt=
ps://forums.autodesk.com/t5/image/serverpage/image-id/46829iC9C1CE720C0A71D=
8?v=3D1.0"></span></p><p><strong>F =3D&nbsp;</strong>344.16 lbs</p><p><stro=
ng>D =3D&nbsp;</strong>0.25 in</p><p><strong>T =3D&nbsp;</strong>(4*344.16)=
/(pi*0.25^2) =3D 7,011.17 psi</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>That is the tensile load t=
hat each bolt experiences, so now we must compare it to the max shear ratin=
g of the bolt. The bolts we use are here:&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.mcmas=
ter.com/91253A537/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">https://www.mc=
master.com/91253A537/</a>. Using the specs here, we can calculate:</p><p>Ac=
tual Shear =3D 7011.17 psi</p><p>Max Shear =3D&nbsp; 120000 psi</p><p>Facto=
r of Safety&nbsp; =3D 120000/7011.17 =3D 17.12</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p=
><p>&nbsp;</p>

